Anonymous Thu 06 Jan 2022 13:35:03 No.44529520 Report
Quoted By: >>44529559
>>44528301
It depends on how complex the story is.
For my new story, the outline was just "meeting PERSON" for the first chapter. After that, I started writing and added in the who/what/where/why/when/how.
Once that's down, it's time to make sure the things you have are pushing the conflict for the chapter and the whole piece (as much as you outlined)
The "bible" comes together at the same time as the first draft. Then I revise and flesh things out, much as an artist is adding details to something they already blocked out using simple shapes (outline) and then sketched (the first draft)

Even though I can't draw because of bad hands, I understand the concept of that first drawn line that anchors what you're doing.
The first overall lesson is learning to hang pieces off of it so it looks seamless.
The later lesson is being able to see that core theme/plot thread as quickly as possible.
